So I can't define concurrency I can only
describe it as sending 3 minions to go do 
some stuff. One could 1) get groceries, 
2) do the laundry, 3) clean the car
and then you could continue watching JJK.

Now any one of these minions could 
be asleep mid journey, or the just stopped
But also these could be doing different tasks 
at the same time. IE while one is walking 
around the shop confused, the other could be  
playing Take 5 on the car stereo, thats parralelism

One thing here is that, you don't control the process
or states of these minions, the either stop, or 
just continue, or they wait for each other

Same with go-routines. The just spin them, the Go Scheduler 
can then map them out to different processors or the same 
processor. We just design or spin up many things and don't
care about them, only results

And when you do need to coordinate these results you easily 
can (not looking at you java). So concurrency is just design
and parallelism is you telling the kernel you know better than it 
or rather, actual execution
